            "summary": "Theme Summary: AI Limitations, Avoidance & Boundary Setting \u2014 Accuracy, Reliability & Hallucination Risk\n\nAcross a wide range of high-stakes professional contexts, users consistently establish deliberate boundaries to avoid over-reliance on AI due to persistent concerns about factual accuracy, reliability, and the pervasive risk of hallucinations. Rather than viewing AI as a autonomous authority, users treat it as a fallible tool whose outputs demand rigorous verification\u2014particularly in domains where errors could compromise credibility, client relationships, regulatory compliance, or educational integrity.\n\nKey use cases reveal a pattern of risk-averse behavior: users actively avoid deploying AI for tasks involving factual reporting (e.g., case law, scientific literature, sports statistics), data analysis, anatomical or technical visualization, academic summarization, and translation\u2014areas where precision is non-negotiable. Repeated experiences with AI-generated fabrications\u2014such as invented citations, misattributed quotes, incorrect acronym expansions, and anatomical distortions\u2014have eroded trust, leading users to prefer manual verification, traditional research methods (e.g., Google, databases like IMDb or Trados), and human expertise. The cost of fact-checking AI outputs often exceeds the time saved by automation, reinforcing the preference for human-led processes.\n\nBeyond content errors, users are frustrated by AI\u2019s overconfidence: its tendency to generate polished, assured responses\u2014even when incorrect\u2014undermines its utility as a diagnostic aid. In response, users adopt adaptive strategies: they engineer prompts with explicit constraints (\u201cDo not assume prior tasks were completed\u201d), demand source citations, probe for logical inconsistencies, and reject conversational embellishments (\u201cI think I found\u2026\u201d preferred over \u201cYou\u2019re exactly right!\u201d). Many intentionally reset sessions or narrow query parameters to mitigate hallucination cascades, treating AI not as a conversational partner, but as a limited data processor requiring constant oversight.\n\nThe emerging consensus is clear: AI\u2019s current capabilities, while useful for ideation or rapid prototyping, remain too unreliable for critical, accuracy-sensitive tasks. Users establish firm boundaries\u2014not out of technological Luddism, but from empirical experience\u2014prioritizing integrity, accountability, and human judgment over convenience. In doing so, they redefine AI\u2019s role: not as a replacement for expertise, but as a supplementary instrument that must be rigorously scrutinized and never trusted implicitly.",
