            "sub_category": "Authenticity & Human Voice Preservation",
            "summary": "**Summary: AI Limitations, Avoidance & Boundary Setting \u2014 With Emphasis on Authenticity & Human Voice Preservation**\n\nIndividuals across diverse professional and personal domains are deliberately restricting or entirely avoiding the use of artificial intelligence in communications and creative tasks where authenticity, emotional nuance, and personal voice are paramount. This intentional avoidance is not rooted in technophobia, but in a principled commitment to preserving human integrity, relational trust, and genuine self-expression. Users consistently report that AI-generated content\u2014however accurate or efficient\u2014tends to sound robotic, overly sanitized, formulaic, or emotionally flat, failing to convey sincerity, urgency, cultural sensitivity, or stylistic individuality. \n\nKey use cases reveal a pattern: AI is accepted only as a limited, secondary tool\u2014for refinement, proofreading, or brainstorming\u2014never as a primary generator of content. In client communications, educational observations, personal messages, branded copy, and culturally significant content, users insist on human-authored drafts to ensure emotional resonance, ethical accuracy, and authentic voice. The fear is not merely of errors, but of erasure: the dilution of personal identity, the erosion of professional credibility, and the alienation of recipients who value human connection over algorithmic convenience. Even when users face personal challenges\u2014such as dyslexia\u2014they opt against AI assistance, prioritizing the relational value of personally crafted communication.\n\nFurthermore, users actively resist the delegation of creative or high-stakes tasks to AI, recognizing its inherent biases\u2014such as agreeableness, tone mismatches, and generic phrasing\u2014as corrosive to authenticity. They report frustration when colleagues bypass them by auto-revising their work with AI, perceiving it as a violation of professional boundaries and a dismissal of their expertise. In technical or culturally sensitive contexts\u2014such as Indigenous knowledge or crafting patterns\u2014AI\u2019s inability to replicate nuanced, context-dependent standards makes manual creation not just preferable, but necessary.\n\nUltimately, this theme reflects a broader ethic of **human-centered technology use**: AI is acknowledged as a tool, not a substitute. Boundaries are consciously drawn to safeguard critical thinking, creative autonomy, and the irreplaceable warmth of human interaction. Authenticity is not an inefficiency to be automated\u2014it is the core value that justifies the extra effort of human labor. In preserving voice, intention, and emotional depth, users affirm that the most meaningful communication cannot be generated\u2014it must be lived, felt, and written by hand.",
