            "sub_category": "Creative & Design Boundary Setting",
            "summary": "**Summary: Creative & Design Boundary Setting in the Face of AI Limitations**\n\nIndividuals across creative and design domains\u2014spanning visual art, graphic design, writing, architecture, and multimedia production\u2014consciously establish strict boundaries against AI involvement in tasks requiring aesthetic judgment, emotional depth, cultural nuance, or personal expression. Despite AI\u2019s growing capabilities in automation and efficiency, users consistently reject its use in final creative outputs due to recurrent limitations: AI-generated visuals and text are frequently deemed low-quality, impersonal, or lacking authenticity; they exhibit poor contextual understanding, fail to replicate human stylistic intent, and often produce generic, undifferentiated, or even misleading content. \n\nKey concerns include the erosion of originality\u2014AI tends to regurgitate formulaic ideas across clients or fail to follow nuanced creative briefs (e.g., generating unavailable startup names or misrepresenting Irish-language content)\u2014and the absence of soul or intentionality in machine-generated work. Users report that AI struggles with precision (e.g., pixel art, logo placement, color harmony), lacks ethical awareness (e.g., intellectual property violations through training on artists\u2019 work), and cannot replicate the iterative, intuitive decision-making that defines skilled human craftsmanship. Importantly, many users express not just a preference but a moral conviction: they value the personal fulfillment, ownership, and authentic voice that emerge from manual creation, viewing creative work as an extension of human identity rather than a task to be optimized.\n\nConsequently, a clear operational boundary emerges: AI is tolerated or even embraced in supporting, non-creative roles\u2014such as technical assistance (e.g., noise removal, brainstorming prompts, or administrative tasks)\u2014but is categorically excluded from final creative output. This boundary is reinforced by practical failures (e.g., time lost correcting AI errors exceeds manual creation time), student and client rejection of AI-generated content, and financial or ethical considerations. Ultimately, users prioritize human agency, artistic integrity, and emotional resonance over efficiency, affirming that true creativity is not a product of algorithmic prediction, but of lived experience, intention, and manual mastery.",
            "usecases": "AI failure in graphic design tasks, Avoid AI for complex or creative tasks, Avoid AI for creative brainstorming, Avoid AI for creative writing tasks, Avoid AI for design and architectural decisions, Avoid AI for visual design and image sourcing, Avoid AI for visual design tasks, Avoid AI for writing and content creation, Avoid AI in creative writing, Avoid AI-generated creative content, Avoiding AI for artwork generation, Avoiding AI for creative alterations, Avoiding AI for pixel art generation, Avoiding AI for visual content due to student preferences, Avoiding AI in creative design tasks, Avoiding AI in creative tasks, Avoiding AI in creative writing, Avoiding AI in graphic design, Avoiding AI in sensitive brainstorming, Avoiding repetitive AI-generated content, Creating graphics manually despite AI options, Creative workflow boundary guardian, Visual design boundary setting"
