          {
            "sub_category": "Technical Quality, Code & Engineering Boundaries",
            "summary": "**Summary: AI Limitations, Avoidance & Boundary Setting \u2014 Technical Quality, Code & Engineering Boundaries**\n\nIn high-stakes software development and technical workflows, users consistently establish firm boundaries around AI usage to preserve code quality, maintain technical ownership, and mitigate systemic risks. Rather than treating AI as a general-purpose coding assistant, experienced engineers treat it as a constrained, context-dependent tool \u2014 one that must be actively monitored, selectively applied, and never trusted to drive critical systems.\n\nCore to this philosophy is the recognition that AI lacks deep contextual understanding, struggles with iterative troubleshooting, and often generates overly generalized, inaccurate, or non-integrable code. Users report frequent failures when AI attempts to replicate existing implementations, refactor large codebases, or navigate domain-specific irregularities (e.g., music theory edge cases or C++/Visual Studio compilation cycles). In these scenarios, AI\u2019s tendency to \u201cgo off-track\u201d through self-correction loops, unsolicited changes, or superficial solutions introduces technical debt, breaks functionality, and erodes system integrity.\n\nTo counter these risks, users enforce strict boundaries: they exclude AI from code review, interpersonal communication, and final implementation \u2014 prioritizing personal mastery, accountability, and maintainability. Many avoid AI entirely for complex tasks, citing past failures where AI-generated code required full rewrites, increased debugging time, or led to loss of institutional knowledge. Even when AI is used for assistance \u2014 such as brainstorming high-level approaches or debugging minor issues \u2014 it is only employed when the user possesses sufficient domain expertise to validate, steer, and correct its output. Otherwise, reliance on AI leads to wasted time, misaligned solutions, and costly escalations.\n\nAdditionally, users adapt pragmatically to AI\u2019s infrastructural limits \u2014 switching platforms due to usage caps or poor quality (e.g., avoiding weak wearable AI models in favor of robust desktop counterparts) \u2014 underscoring that reliability, not convenience, governs tool selection. The overarching principle is clear: AI is not a substitute for engineering judgment. It is a supplementary aid, useful only within tightly defined parameters where human oversight ensures precision, context-awareness, and long-term system health. By consciously limiting AI\u2019s scope, technical teams preserve code quality, sustain expertise, and safeguard against the hidden costs of algorithmic overreach.",
            "usecases": "AI as a non-reliable backup tool, AI collaboration limitations in frontend debugging, AI failure in replicating existing implementations, AI for overcoming wearable tech limitations, AI tool switching due to limits, AI-assisted troubleshooting with limitations, AI-induced debugging frustration, Avoid AI code that is too generalized, Avoid AI in communication and code review, Avoid AI-induced rabbit holes with limited expertise, Avoiding AI for critical code development, Avoiding AI for large-scale refactoring, Avoiding AI in coding tasks, Avoiding AI-generated code due to quality risks, Hardcoding domain-specific exceptions over algorithmic generation, Over-reliance on AI leading to technical debt, Prevent AI from going off-track during coding, Systematic troubleshooting limitation awareness"
          }
